    <weatherForecast/>
    <avalancheActivity>
      <highlights>Wind slabs represent the main danger.</highlights>
      <comment>The wind slabs of the last few days are lying on the unfavourable surface of an old snowpack in particular on steep shady slopes. &lt;br/> As a consequence of the southeasterly wind they have increased in size moderately on Wednesday. &lt;br/> Especially adjacent to ridgelines and in gullies and bowls extremely steep terrain: The wind slabs can be released by a single winter sport participant in some cases. &lt;br/> The backcountry touring conditions are generally favourable. Wind slabs require caution.</comment>
    </avalancheActivity>
    <snowpackStructure>
      <comment>On Sunday, at an altitude of around 1,500 metres, 50 to 100 cm of snow fell widely across the eastern and south-eastern parts of the region, and 30 to 40 cm of snow fell across the rest of the area. The weather conditions facilitated a settling of the snowpack. &lt;br/> The surface of the snowpack will freeze to form a strong crust. Sunshine and high temperatures will give rise from the middle of the day to gradual softening of the snowpack on steep sunny slopes at low and intermediate altitudes. &lt;br/> Especially adjacent to ridgelines in all aspects: The sometimes strong wind has transported the new snow. Here snow depths vary greatly, depending on the infuence of the wind. &lt;br/> Weak layers exist in the snowpack in particular on steep shady slopes.</comment>
    </snowpackStructure>
    <travelAdvisory/>
    <tendency>
      <highlights>The weather conditions will facilitate a gradual strengthening of the near-surface layers in particular on sunny slopes. The various wind slabs have bonded with the old snowpack.</highlights>
      <tendencyType>steady</tendencyType>
